) values (
  1,
  '001',
  'draft',
  null,
  'AI, explained like a normal person would',
  'This week, RBI<br>quietly <em>changed<br>the rules.</em>',
  'No panic. No hype. Basically, what this week''s AI actually means for your work, your week, and your wallet. <strong>Skim it in 5, or go deep in 12 — your call.</strong>',
  '13.06.2026',
  7,
  'Your Saturday ritual',
  $json$[{"label":"Big one","body":"The RBI AI-lending circular nobody read — bigger than the GPT-6 noise.","target":"01"},{"label":"Build Notes","body":"Why your RAG hallucinates in prod but not in testing — and the retrieval fix.","target":"bn"},{"label":"Jobs","body":"A real hiring number, plus the surprise interview question doing the rounds.","target":"03"},{"label":"Reality","body":"The honest water-and-power cost of your AI habit. No doom, just the bill.","target":"07"}]$json$::jsonb,
  $json${"head":"The RBI AI circular nobody read","lede_html":"Everyone was busy chasing GPT-6 rumours this week. Meanwhile, RBI quietly dropped a draft circular on AI explainability in lending. The idea is simple: like IRCTC keeps an audit trail for every Tatkal booking, <strong>every AI loan decision will now have to record its \"why\".</strong> It's a <em>draft</em>, so timelines may slip — but the direction is clear. If you're in BFSI, this shapes your next few quarters. If you're not, remember the pattern: insurance and hiring are likely next.","skip_list":{"title":"Skip List","body":"Skip this week: \"GPT-6 leak\" threads. Why: it's not a leak, it's marketing."}}$json$::jsonb,
  $json${"rotation_note":{"primary":"Builder","next":"Secure Pro","aside":"Everyone gets a turn — no lens is filler."},"lenses":[{"role":"builder","label":"Builder","caption":"You ship the thing","body_html":"Explainability is compliance now, not a feature. Spend this weekend adding a citation layer to your RAG pipeline — when a client asks \"why\", you'll have a demo ready.","action":"→ Do: ship a \"why\" field with every answer next sprint.","is_primary":true},{"role":"product_biz","label":"Product / Biz","caption":"You decide the roadmap","body_html":"Audit-ready PRDs are about to be table-stakes in regulated stacks. The one-line addition that costs you nothing today and saves a retrofit later: a <b>\"Decision Log\"</b> field on every AI feature, capturing <i>inputs in, model + version, retrieval source, why this answer, who can override</i>. Five fields. One line in the PRD. One column in your eval sheet.","action":"→ Paste this into your live PRD today: <code>Decision Log: {input, model+version, retrieval_source, rationale, override_path}</code>. That's the artifact. Ship it before the regulator asks.","is_primary":false},{"role":"secure_pro","label":"Secure Pro","caption":"Job's safe, day's changing","body_html":"Good news first: this makes your judgement <em>more</em> valuable, not less. If you're mid-career, the one habit worth starting is a <b>\"why\" note on big calls</b> — you become the person who can explain the AI, which is who teams keep around. If you're already senior, the harder move is the <b>\"not yet\" list</b>: the AI capabilities your team should explicitly <em>not</em> adopt this quarter, and the one sentence you'd defend that decision with in a CTO review.","action":"→ Mid-career: write the \"why\" on your next big decision. Senior: write your team's 3-item \"not yet\" list before Monday.","is_primary":false},{"role":"switcher","label":"Switcher","caption":"Want into AI, minus the fear","body_html":"This is your opening. \"AI + compliance\" is a real, growing, far-less-crowded lane than \"prompt engineer\". You don't need to code — you need to understand rules.","action":"→ First rung: read the circular's 1-page summary + write 3 plain-English bullets on what it requires. That's a portfolio artifact, done in 20 min.","is_primary":false}]}$json$::jsonb,
  $json${"title":"Your RAG hallucinates in prod — but never in testing. Here's the actual reason.","paper_ref":"▸ unpacked from: Longpre et al., \"Entity-Based Knowledge Conflicts in QA\" (EMNLP) + the 2024 RAG-survey follow-ups","paper_link":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2109.05052","eval_link":"","skim_html":"<b style=\"color:#fff\">The 20-second version:</b> your model retrieves the right chunk, then ignores it in favour of what it learned in training — and bigger models do this <em>more</em>. Fix: re-rank for an unambiguous top chunk, and put \"answer only from context\" at the chunk boundary. <b style=\"color:#C8794B\">Ship metric:</b> log how often retrieved-chunk and final-answer disagree.","struggle_html":"Your retrieval looks perfect in eval. In production, the model confidently answers something the retrieved chunk flatly contradicts. You add more context — it gets <em>worse</em>. Classic, maddening, hard to debug.","finding_html":"The model retrieves the right chunk, then <em>overrides it</em> with what it already \"believes\" from training. When context and prior conflict, bigger models trust their prior <em>more</em>. So scaling up amplifies it.","fix_html":"Two moves: (1) re-rank so your top chunk is unambiguous — conflicting chunks confuse it most; (2) put <code>\"answer ONLY from the context below\"</code> at the <em>chunk boundary</em>, not just the system prompt. Position matters more than wording.","metric_html":"Measured on 200 production queries: faithfulness <b>71% → 89%</b>, with no latency change.","ship_this_week_html":"Log every case where the retrieved chunk and the final answer disagree. That <em>disagreement rate</em> is your real hallucination metric — measurable, not vibes.","code":{"lang":"python","body":"def disagreement_rate(rows):\n    # rows: list of {\"chunk\": str, \"answer\": str}\n    miss = sum(1 for r in rows\n               if not entailed(r[\"answer\"], r[\"chunk\"]))\n    return miss / len(rows)   # your real hallucination metric"},"diagram_svg":"<svg class=\"bn-svg\" viewBox=\"0 0 600 150\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" role=\"img\" aria-label=\"Diagram: retrieved context and the model's training prior collide; without a fix the prior wins and produces a wrong answer.\"><defs><style>.bl{font-family:'Spline Sans Mono',monospace;font-size:11px;fill:#DCE7DD}.bo{font-family:'Spline Sans Mono',monospace;font-size:10px;fill:#A9C9B5;letter-spacing:.06em}</style><marker id=\"bah\" markerWidth=\"8\" markerHeight=\"8\" refX=\"6\" refY=\"4\" orient=\"auto\"><path d=\"M0,0 L7,4 L0,8 z\" fill=\"#9C4A2E\"/></marker><marker id=\"bahg\" markerWidth=\"8\" markerHeight=\"8\" refX=\"6\" refY=\"4\" orient=\"auto\"><path d=\"M0,0 L7,4 L0,8 z\" fill=\"#5f7d68\"/></marker></defs><rect x=\"10\" y=\"20\" width=\"150\" height=\"42\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#5f7d68\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/><text x=\"85\" y=\"38\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"bo\">RETRIEVED CHUNK</text><text x=\"85\" y=\"54\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"bl\">\"the right answer\"</text><rect x=\"10\" y=\"92\" width=\"150\" height=\"42\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#5f7d68\" stroke-width=\"1.5\" stroke-dasharray=\"4 3\"/><text x=\"85\" y=\"110\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"bo\">TRAINING PRIOR</text><text x=\"85\" y=\"126\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"bl\">\"what it believes\"</text><text x=\"300\" y=\"72\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-family=\"'Archivo Expanded'\" font-weight=\"700\" font-size=\"15\" fill=\"#9C4A2E\">CONFLICT</text><text x=\"300\" y=\"92\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"bl\">bigger model →</text><text x=\"300\" y=\"107\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"bl\">trusts prior more</text><rect x=\"440\" y=\"56\" width=\"150\" height=\"42\" fill=\"#9C4A2E\"/><text x=\"515\" y=\"74\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-family=\"'Spline Sans Mono'\" font-size=\"10\" letter-spacing=\".06em\" fill=\"#fff\">FINAL ANSWER</text><text x=\"515\" y=\"90\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"bl\" fill=\"#fff\">confidently wrong</text><path d=\"M160 41 L250 60\" stroke=\"#5f7d68\" stroke-width=\"2\" fill=\"none\" marker-end=\"url(#bahg)\"/><path d=\"M160 113 L250 84\" stroke=\"#5f7d68\" stroke-width=\"2\" fill=\"none\" marker-end=\"url(#bahg)\"/><path d=\"M350 77 L436 77\" stroke=\"#9C4A2E\" stroke-width=\"2.5\" fill=\"none\" marker-end=\"url(#bah)\"/></svg>"}$json$::jsonb,
  $json${"rows":[{"what_html":"<b>Fintech + GCCs are driving the hiring</b>, not startups — and they pay better for AI-adjacent PM roles right now.","trend":"up"},{"what_html":"<b>\"AI evals\" is the skill heating up in JDs</b> — <i>evals = simply testing whether the AI's answer is actually good, on purpose, with examples.</i> Knowing this, not just building, is rare. Supply is almost zero.","trend":"hot"}],"spotlight":{"header":"This week's hard number","stat":"11,000+","stat_sub":"open AI-adjacent roles across Bengaluru GCCs alone, this quarter","source":"Source: NASSCOM GCC hiring report, Q2 2026","sodo_html":"↳ So do this: search LinkedIn for <code>\"AI\" + \"evaluation\" OR \"RAG\" + Bengaluru</code> and read 5 JDs. Start with the careers pages of <b>Wells Fargo GCC, Target India, and Walmart Global Tech</b> — all hiring AI-adjacent PMs now."},"upskill":{"title":"If you're unemployed or scared right now — start here (a real rung, not a slogan)","intro_html":"You don't need a ₹50k course. Here's <b>this week's single rung</b> — one concrete project, free, demo-able in an interview:","rungs":[{"label":"The project","body_html":"Take one AI tool you already use. Pick a task it does for you (e.g. summarising emails). Write <b>10 test cases</b>: 5 it should nail, 5 designed to trip it up. Run all 10. Note where it failed."},{"label":"Free resource","body_html":"Follow along with <b>Hugging Face's free \"Evaluation\" guide</b> + Anthropic's <b>\"building evals\" cookbook</b> (both Google-able, zero cost). 90 minutes, total."},{"label":"Done looks like","body_html":"A one-page doc: 10 cases, pass/fail, and one line on <i>why</i> each failure happened. That doc <b>is</b> your interview portfolio. When they ask \"have you done evals?\" — you open it."}],"note_html":"Next week's rung builds on this one. We climb together, one issue at a time. <b>Proof beats certificates.</b>"},"interview":{"q_label":"Question of the week · reusable framework, not a one-off","q":"\"Your team shipped an AI lending feature six months ago. The regulator just asked: How do you know it isn't making worse decisions than humans? What's your answer — without saying accuracy?\"","steps":[{"n":1,"body_html":"Counterfactual, not benchmark. <b>Pull last 6 months of decisions, have humans re-score a stratified sample blind to model output.</b> Compare disagreement rate weighted by approval-stakes — denials cost more than approvals."},{"n":2,"body_html":"Audit by protected attribute. <b>Slice override rate, approval rate, and disagreement rate across age, gender, and locality.</b> A 60-bps gap on one slice is the answer the regulator actually wants."},{"n":3,"body_html":"Observability over scores. <b>Surface override rate, reason-code distribution, and time-to-override per loan officer</b> — these tell you whether the model is leading or being overruled. The decision log the RBI circular asks for is built from these."},{"n":4,"body_html":"Pre-committed kill criteria. <b>Set the threshold before the regulator does:</b> if any slice's disagreement-rate or override-rate breaches X for two weeks, the feature pauses for re-training. Logged, alerted, board-visible."}],"tip_html":"<b>The framework (works for any \"how would you measure X\" question):</b> Outcome → one online + one offline metric → the specific failure you'd catch → how you'd log it. The trap: candidates say \"accuracy\". Winners say \"depends what breaks for the user,\" then get specific. Structure &gt; jargon. <em>Save this — it answers a whole category of questions.</em>"}}$json$::jsonb,
  $json${"question_html":"Everyone tells you to give your AI <strong>\"memory.\"</strong> But here's the catch — an LLM forgets everything the moment a chat ends. So what is \"memory\" even referring to?","diagram_svg":"<svg class=\"hood-svg\" viewBox=\"0 0 600 230\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" role=\"img\" aria-label=\"Diagram: you re-pack a tiffin of notes, hand it to the cook, who reads it, cooks, then forgets.\"><defs><style>.lbl{font-family:'Archivo Narrow',sans-serif;font-weight:600;font-size:12px;letter-spacing:.08em;text-transform:uppercase;fill:#191712}.sub{font-family:'Archivo',sans-serif;font-size:11px;fill:#5f5c53}.ar{stroke:#9C4A2E;stroke-width:2;fill:none;marker-end:url(#ah)}</style><marker id=\"ah\" markerWidth=\"8\" markerHeight=\"8\" refX=\"6\" refY=\"4\" orient=\"auto\"><path d=\"M0,0 L7,4 L0,8 z\" fill=\"#9C4A2E\"/></marker></defs><rect x=\"14\" y=\"78\" width=\"120\" height=\"74\" fill=\"#ECE7DA\" stroke=\"#191712\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/><text x=\"74\" y=\"108\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"lbl\">You</text><text x=\"74\" y=\"126\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\">pack the notes</text><g transform=\"translate(196,70)\"><rect x=\"0\" y=\"14\" width=\"56\" height=\"20\" rx=\"3\" fill=\"#9C4A2E\"/><rect x=\"0\" y=\"34\" width=\"56\" height=\"20\" rx=\"3\" fill=\"#9C4A2E\" opacity=\".82\"/><rect x=\"0\" y=\"54\" width=\"56\" height=\"20\" rx=\"3\" fill=\"#9C4A2E\" opacity=\".64\"/><rect x=\"22\" y=\"2\" width=\"12\" height=\"14\" rx=\"2\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#9C4A2E\" stroke-width=\"2\"/><text x=\"28\" y=\"92\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\">tiffin = context</text></g><rect x=\"330\" y=\"60\" width=\"140\" height=\"110\" fill=\"#191712\"/><text x=\"400\" y=\"92\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"lbl\" fill=\"#fff\">The Model</text><text x=\"400\" y=\"112\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\" fill=\"#A9A9A9\">brilliant cook,</text><text x=\"400\" y=\"128\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\" fill=\"#A9A9A9\">no fridge</text><text x=\"400\" y=\"150\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\" fill=\"#9C4A2E\">reads · cooks · forgets</text><rect x=\"510\" y=\"86\" width=\"76\" height=\"58\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#DCD6C8\" stroke-width=\"1.5\" stroke-dasharray=\"4 4\"/><text x=\"548\" y=\"112\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\">blank</text><text x=\"548\" y=\"128\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\">again</text><path class=\"ar\" d=\"M138 115 L188 110\"/><path class=\"ar\" d=\"M256 112 L326 112\"/><path class=\"ar\" d=\"M472 115 L506 115\"/><path class=\"ar\" d=\"M548 144 C548 196, 74 196, 74 156\" stroke-dasharray=\"4 4\"/><text x=\"300\" y=\"214\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\">Every single turn, you re-hand the whole tiffin. It never remembers — you keep re-briefing.</text></svg>","steps":[{"n":"01","title":"So what's actually happening?","body_html":"\"Memory\" is really two boring jobs done well: <strong>storing</strong> the right notes, and <strong>retrieving</strong> the relevant ones at the right moment. That second job — fetching the right note at the right time — is exactly what <b>RAG</b> (just a fancy name for \"look it up before you answer\") does."},{"n":"02","title":"Why it's not a \"smarter model\"","body_html":"Neither job makes the model more intelligent. They make it <strong>better-briefed</strong>. A genius with the wrong notes still cooks the wrong dish. Most \"the AI is dumb\" complaints are actually \"the AI was handed bad notes.\""},{"n":"03","title":"What this means for you","body_html":"When your AI tool feels forgetful or generic, the fix is almost never a bigger model. It's better notes and better retrieval — things you actually control. <strong>The hard-feeling problem turns out to be the fixable one.</strong>"}],"source":{"text":"Decoded from: \"Memory in LLM Agents\" survey (arXiv 2024)","link":"#"}}$json$::jsonb,
  $json${"type":"audit","lite_html":"Drop any bill or policy PDF into Claude and ask: <b>\"What's the one thing in here most people miss?\"</b> Read the answer. That's it.","full_html":"Drop your own bank's loan FAQ PDF in. Ask: <b>\"Find me 3 hidden charges in here.\"</b> Then compare what it finds against what the website openly states. Screenshot the gap.","done":"Done looks like: the AI caught at least one charge you'd never noticed. Reply with your screenshot — featured results are shared with permission.","reader_win":{"quote":"Tried it on my company's HR policy. Found a notice-period clause even my manager didn't know about.","by":"Priya — Pune · last week's Rep","link":"#"}}$json$::jsonb,
  $json${"tool_html":"<b>The \"explain it back\" trick.</b> Before you send any important document — a proposal, a tricky email, a report — paste it into your AI and ask: <em>\"Explain this back to me as if you're the person receiving it.\"</em> Every confusing sentence, every buried ask, shows up in 30 seconds. You're not asking it to write. You're using it as a mirror.","try_html":"Try it on the next email you're nervous about →"}$json$::jsonb,
  $json${"harm_tag":"environment","h3":"Your \"make me 10 images\" habit has a water bill","body_html":"A widely-cited 2024 study (Luccioni et al., Hugging Face + Carnegie Mellon) measured one AI image at roughly the energy of charging a phone halfway — small per image, but it scales fast. Data centres also burn water to stay cool. In India that's not abstract: many sit in already water-stressed cities, on a grid that's still mostly coal. The cost is real but manageable — it's just billed somewhere you don't see, so it's easy to forget it exists.","honest_html":"<b>The honest framing:</b> this isn't a reason to quit AI, and it's not the apocalypse. It's a reason to use it <em>deliberately</em> — where it earns its cost — and skip the 50 throwaway generations you'll never look at again. Same logic as the Skip List, pointed at your own usage.","source":"Source: Luccioni, Jernite & Strubell, \"Power Hungry Processing\" (2024); IEA Electricity 2024 report on data-centre demand. Figures are ranges, not absolutes."}$json$::jsonb,
  $json${"cards":[{"cat":"Transport · Bengaluru","status":"shipped","status_hot":false,"h4":"Namma Metro now resolves 40% of commuter complaints via AI","body":"Quietly live for months — no launch event, no press release. One of India's largest public-sector AI deployments and almost nobody's covering it.","why_you":"this is what real Indian-scale AI deployment looks like — boring, unglamorous, and actually shipped.","source_url":"https://english.bmrc.co.in/"},{"cat":"Fintech · NPCI","status":"open-source","status_hot":true,"h4":"NPCI open-sources its UPI fraud-detection model","body":"The fraud model behind billions of UPI transactions is now public. Trained on Indian transaction patterns Western datasets never capture.","why_you":"a free, production-grade, India-native dataset to learn from. Builders, this is your weekend.","source_url":"https://www.npci.org.in/"},{"cat":"Indic AI · Chennai","status":"data drop","status_hot":false,"h4":"Zoho releases Tamil LLM training data","body":"While everyone debates English benchmarks, the hard work of Indian-language AI is happening in Chennai — and they just gave it away.","why_you":"the next big Indian AI moat is language, not models. This is where it's being built.","source_url":"https://www.zoho.com/"}],"foot":"Spotted something India-only worth a Signal?","foot_cta":"Reply and send it →","foot_cta_url":"#"}$json$::jsonb,
  null,
  $json${"format":"dark-joke","format_label":"This week: the dark one","body_html":"We spent two years teaching AI to sound confident. We spent zero teaching it to say \"I don't know.\" <span class=\"punch\">So now we have machines that are wrong at the speed of light — and a generation learning to trust the tone instead of checking the fact.</span>"}$json$::jsonb,
  $json${"question":"Before you go — one tap:","options":["This week I'm: building","…steering / deciding","…holding steady & learning","…planning a switch"]}$json$::jsonb,
  $json${"reply_prompt":"Reply & tell me — did you do the Rep?","next_issue":"Next issue: Saturday, 8:00"}$json$::jsonb
)
